ECLOGUE V.——DAPHNIS.

ARGUMENT.—Two shepherds, Mopsus and Menalcas, challenge each other to a musical contest (V. 1—19) : Mopsus begins aud bewails the death of Daphnis (V. 20—44): Menalcas sings the heavenly life of Daphnis ancl his admission into the society of the gods (V. 56-80).

The death of Daphnis was a favourite subject with the pastoral poets (Cf. Theocr. Id. I.); as also was the death of Adonis. In each case the subject was the fate of a beautiful youth who came to an untimely end. The legend is supposed to be of Phoenician origin. So Milton says (Paradise Lost, Book I):

Thammuz came next behind, Whose annual wound in Lebanon allured The Syrian damsels to lament his sate In ainorous ditties all a summer’s day; While smooth Adonis from his native roek Rau purple 'to tho sea—supposed with blood Of Thaniniuz yearly wouuded.
